segments.text: Share with me any recollections you have and or any thoughts you think Dr. Williams would have had about some of these special people.
Ed Cooper, who was his assistant for many years.
Ed was a good assistant.
He would have thought Ed was a good assistant.
And he would ask him to do anything, I believe.
Do you remember any Cooper stories?
Any stories about Cooper and
Things that he and Dr. Williams...
I remember the last thing I heard about him.
What's that?
Cut it off.
Oh, no.
Go ahead.
Go ahead.
About something else then.
You know, I told you a while ago about Williams is out and Jarvis is in.
Oh, mm-hmm.
Do you remember any stories about things that Dr. Williams asked Ed to do?
Any assignments he gave him?
I gave him one early.
That was to look after his mother when they had the musical and the reception down at Bryan.
And when they first came, Ed was the one he asked to take care of his mother because he and I were in the receiving line.
But Ed evidently just did anything they asked.
And I can't...
I wasn't that close to what Jack was having people do.
I was sort of closed off because I didn't try to be a part of his work, only when he included me.
All right, now, who do you think were the closest confidants, trustees of Dr. Williams when he was at A&M?
Who did he trust most when he...
listen to or to give an assignment to?
Who would have been the people that he trusted most?
I don't think he would have had one person singled out.
No, no, but who were in the group?
Well, his staff.
But which one?
I don't know.
He would have asked many more.
He would have just taken everybody.
His philosophy was give that person their job, pick the best person you can.
You've heard this before.
Let them do their job.
Now, you probably were closer to who he was using than I was because he didn't come home and recount the events of the day.
I sometimes overheard

For instance, when we lived here, I didn't know what he was doing until we went out to his head of his department for a happy hour, and Carl would be dying laughing and repeating what he had found out that Jack was doing.
But I wouldn't have known if I hadn't listened to Carl.
He just didn't come home and say, I did this today or did that.
But like I know that John Calhoun and John Colas and Ed Cooper...
He would have talked to them if it related to their work.
That's when he would have approached him about what had to be done.
But I don't think, I know he got up and went to people's office to talk to them.
He didn't send for you.
Did he come to your office?
A few times, yes, ma'am.
He didn't send for you, though, did he?
Occasionally.
Did he?
Occasionally.
Like that day on the law school and the medical school.
And when we walked in, he was grinning, and we kind of like, uh-oh.
This one's going to be fun.
It was not a mean grin.
It was like, okay.
You're here.
You're happy.
Happy Jack.
Smiling Jack.
Now, was he, where did that nickname begin?
Do you know?
With the students, Smiling Jack.
Here at Clemson?
Okay.
In his Cowboys and Indians course.
He taught the opening of the West, and they called it Cowboys and Indians.
Of the courses he taught, which one do you, which course or courses do you think he enjoyed most?
Don't have any idea.
Okay.
Do you know of any that he taught that he didn't enjoy?
No.
What did he like most about teaching?
Why did he?
I don't know.
I know he was the type of person that wanted to be a good teacher.
When he went off to get his doctorate, he destroyed all of his lecture notes.
He said, I'm not going to be the kind of professor that writes one set of lectures and then uses them forever.
And so when he came back, he set a time limit for himself.
We came back in spring, and he had to do his research.
And then he taught, and he had to write all those lectures over at the same time he was writing his dissertation.
But I don't think he, he hadn't realized that was going to happen to him, but he did it.
Now what was his dissertation topic?
Crime and Punishment in the Old South.
Okay.
I've been trying to remember the two times that something excited me till I couldn't go to sleep, and I can only remember one of them.

And it was two things that he did that excited me, and it certainly wasn't when we moved on to another job, but the first one was when the word came that the University of South Carolina was going to publish his dissertation.
Now that just excited me because I had lived through every bit of it.
But I've been trying to remember what was the other thing that was just that exciting something
that pleased him, obviously, something that, but I can't remember.
Now, was he excited about the news that it was going to be published?
He never acted excited about anything.
He'd make a statement and that was it, and he never, you know, made a big deal out of anything.
And one of the schools, the colleges or schools in this state used his dissertation as their textbook as how to write one.
Have you ever seen it?
Oh, yes.
Who would have been, if I were to ask him about who his role models were for good teaching, reckon who he would say?
Who were his models for being a good teacher?
I don't have any idea.
I wonder, was Bell Wiley one?
I don't have any idea.
Who... What...
administrators were his.
Andy Holt?
They were friends.
He enjoyed Andy.
I don't have any idea.
You know, he did so much for Southern Association that he had been exposed to an awful lot of people and Jack was always an officer and everything that he got near before it was over.
That doesn't sound very nice for me to say, but it happened.
You know, ministering or getting things done, I think, showed up.
Other people recognized it.
Excuse me.
He had many, many stories that he used in his speeches and everything.
And I have made notes about some of those that I have used over and over again.
What do you think were some of his favorite stories that he enjoyed telling in his speeches?
The only one I remember was he did quote Thurber.
He quoted Thurber several times.
The Barrel of Bricks story.
And that's the only ones I know.
Do you know where the Barrel of Bricks story came from, where it originated?
No, no.
But I've seen him get up and change his introduction.
At Emory & Henry one time, a student got up to speak before he did.
He was being honored that day.
She got up and told a negative story about something that the students didn't like.
He got up and changed his introduction to quote Thurber about somebody that got eaten for dinner.
I've forgotten how the story went, but I could see how quick he could make a change in a story.
And I recognized it, that he got up and changed it completely to start his speech, just to refer back with a Thurber story on what he had thought of what that child did.
When he was going to make a formal speech,
These are not just remarks.
This is a formal speech.
Did he write it out word for word, or did he have an outline?
He had different ways.
He had note cards.
For years, he taught students here in church.
Then he taught the senior class, the adult class.
And he would get his lesson up a week before time, put it on cards, and then he wouldn't take the cards out of his pocket.
Now, this was at what church?
Methodist.
He wouldn't take the cards out.
And I would sit there hoping.
But he says, if you've written it, you know it.
And I have found that to be true.
The little speech I was going to make for the ceremony out there...
After I wrote it, I could have given it without any notes, and probably I wanted to give Jo something.
I want her to see those pictures of the ceremony so she can see Dalton.
No, the time...
I don't want this on there.
Turn it off.
He'd been teaching in the classroom and in the church, and he always read when he died...
He had given the chairman of his board a book, and the chairman came out and said, I've read more than he did because Jack had the same book.
And I didn't say, no, but Jack was reading three books.
But he read all the time, and he had grown up reading, and he was just that type of a person.
He had great pleasure in it.
Now, he just loved Thurber, all the Thurber stories.
He could relate to those.
But he also read serious things.
But he could write his speeches, and if you'd written your speech, then you could give it without notes.
Do you remember any time when he forgot to get a speech ready or he took the wrong notes?
You wouldn't have been with him the time that he was with the Aggies.
I think I've told you this.
Buck Wires said, Jack, I don't know what you can do.
This is in a gymnasium, and it's a family affair.
People have come and brought their families, their children here in the audience.
And he said it was the most remarkable thing he had.
Buck told me this person, most remarkable thing I've ever seen.
He got up and gave the lessons of history.
He gave them a history lesson.
And he said everybody was quiet and everybody listened.
Now, was that his delivery?
He wouldn't have had any notes.
But you ought to see that book.
Now, it's marked up.

and but he'd write to here and then he'd write to page so and so in a book and you know he could outline it in in the book and i have them in my fireproof safe now one of my favorite williams memories also is that letter from the
person in West Texas that said, I couldn't believe they'd picked you.
You're not an Aggie?
You're not an Aggie.
And I use that quite often.
I give...
But don't tell them that he made it up now.
No, no, no, I don't.
I tell them that it is a story, it is a letter that I heard him quote quite often.
Well, that's what he did.
He went to Buckwires with it, after he composed it, and said, now this sort of covers that problem.
And I thought it was clever, didn't you?
Oh, it always went over speed.
Yeah, it was clever.
You've heard it.
And with groups today, I use it quite often to... You're not an Aggie, but I'll watch you damn close.
And one lady one time, I was standing close enough to her, and she said, I wonder why he said close.
Instead of closely, you know.
And the other one said, I guess he wrote it, I guess it was written the way he talked.
That's right, that's right.
But I could hear, sometimes you hear things, you know, if they don't realize that you're, but no, don't tell me that he composed that to make a point.
I thought it was better than saying I'm not an Aggie, but I'll do the best I can.
That's great.
When y'all traveled, what was his favorite place or places for y'all to visit for relaxation, other than visiting family?
Were there any favorite vacation spots?
No, we toured some.
We took our children, went to Canada, took our children and went out to Outer Banks of North Carolina.
We went in to see one of the
out north place they had up there on the coast.
You said Hawaii.
He wanted to take me.
We never got there.
Oh, you never got there.
We never got there.
Disaster struck both times, and Betty was afraid that I'd never go after Jack died.
But they arranged for Mary for me to go.
and share their facilities.
No, he wanted to move there when the war was over, but he said to me, he said, I just couldn't do it to your parents.
And he never went back to Saipan after?
No, no.
He never went back to Hawaii.
But he wanted to live there because he just loved it because of the weather, because of the breeze, really.
He just loved the fact that if it rained, the breeze dried you off in a few minutes, and it was always this wonderful weather.
Now, as I look back at the notes I made, I remember that 1976, we were looking forward to it on the campus as the centennial.
And all of those great plans were marred by his heart problems.
Were there any warnings before that heart attack?
Sure.
Is that right?
They started here.
Is that right?
He was misdiagnosed.
And the doctor said it was.
hyperglycemia.
But Jack had had trouble for years.
And that's the reason, when we lived in College Station, people didn't know it.
But I did all the grocery shopping.
I did our meals.
I wasn't going to let anybody cook for him.
And that got me in trouble with Juanita, who resented the fact that I couldn't.
But I thought that she liked to make fattening casseroles.
And that wasn't the way I fed my husband.
So what foods did you try to avoid from his diet?
Well, just heavy calories, you know, a balanced diet.
Fruit, vegetables, meat.
By this time, I think I'd stopped frying chicken.
Could he, if he wanted to, privately have a glass of wine or a glass of beer?
Until he got on his medication.
When he got on his medication, it gave him diarrhea.
That was after the heart attack?
Uh-huh.
And that was an experimental drug, you know, that he was on.
But he could have a...
But he didn't drink.
Two drinks would have knocked him out, I think.
He was very sensitive to alcohol.
Now, the heart attack came in March, right?
It was a holiday weekend.
He went up to make an address at Emory & Henry.
It must have been in the spring because he made an address.
He'd already been to the doctor and college station.
And he went up and made his speech.
And then I saw him go in and take a step around the corner and take a pill, because they were giving us a tour of the campus.
And then we were supposed to go to see his mother, and I begged him just to go home.
And we got over to his mother.
He said, mother's expecting me.
It's so lucky.
Got over there, and we went out to eat again.
And he ordered country ham.
And I was trying my best from the other end of the table to catch his eye, and I didn't manage, so he ate another heavy meal.
And so when we got back to his mother's house, I made an excuse and said, we have to go to bed.
We went to bed, and he went to sleep, and I lay there all night long like this, with my hand touching his heart.
The next morning, he got up, went down.
I said, tell your mother that Margaret
I don't remember where I told her I had a kidney stone or what, that we might have to leave suddenly.
I was afraid to leave.
It was a holiday weekend.
And I knew if we canceled our plane and tried to get on an early one, we might be out and not have anything.
We got back, and I said, let's go to the hospital, and we got off the plane in Houston.
He said, no, I've got to go look after my business.
I've got to go Dallas tomorrow or something like that.
So we went to the house, and he called the doctor, and they said, get down here as fast as you can.
And he went to the office and answered his mail.
Because he's so like him.
And then we drove down there.
And I went back to take care of the dog, as I've told you before.
And on Wednesday, the doctor called me up and said he's either had a heart attack.
I have the piece of paper where he listed every time he had a pain and the time and the duration.
And when the doctor came in the next day, he called me and said, I'm taking him to intensive care.
He's either had a heart attack or he's having one.
But you see what I'm saying is you couldn't stop him from doing what he thought he needed to do, and he could have died.
Now, did Dr. DeBakey assist while you all were in Houston?
He was on Jack's case and had every doctor in Houston on the case.
That's what I thought.
And he would not let Jack die.
He saved his life, and he operated on him.
And it was a long time before Jack was, you know, was awake.
And when he was awake, he was awake.
You know, it wasn't that he was mentally gone.
He was just unconscious all that time.
Because it was a month or so, wasn't it?
It was a good while.
It was years.
But when he woke up, it's like John Calhoun, his great assistant told people not to come to see him.
You know who that was.
Anyway, John Calhoun came over and Jack was discussing the university business with him.
He went back and said, well, he's just talking about everything like he did before, and it didn't seem to have, all that time didn't seem to have bothered him.
There's no brain damage.
which was, you know, the hospital, it seemed to that.
But I had the paper that was written on his condition by one of the graduate students there at the hospital, and his whole case was published in one of the medical magazines or whatever it was.
You don't call them magazines, you call them... One of the journals?
Yeah, a journal.
But it was...
But I found out in 1955 about this.
When Murray was six months old that this was a heart condition, but it was big diagnosed.
And when he went to the doctor over on the campus, he still didn't catch it.
When he went to the dentist with the pain in his jaw, the dentist didn't catch it.
And Jack could keep going regardless.
It's been his life.
Keep going regardless of what it was.
If he hadn't learned it before the Marine Corps, he would have learned it in the Marine Corps.
Now, I've heard a story that Dr. DeBakey came to you in the wee hours one morning and asked you to sign some kind of permission for him to use a special drug or a special technique.
I don't know what I signed.
One night I got a phone call that said that Dr. DeBakey feels like he should operate before morning.
And they came up.
We had all undressed.
Roger was there.
We went out in the hallway of the apartment.
Roger Miller.
He stayed with me all that time.
Went out in the hallway in their night clothes because we had opened the two sofas in the room where the girls and I slept.
And Roger had the bedroom.
And so we just all went out there, and the doctor came up and explained to us.
And he moved to Florida, that doctor.
I shouldn't remember his name, too.
I could remember all these names if I wasn't just yakking like this.
Explained us what they were going to do.
And Dr. DeBakey had gone home to take a nap.
And then he operated.
And of course, we sat up the rest of the night.
And then when the phone go off, they had us come down to his office.
And they told us that everything had been fine.
And Dr. DeBakey, after a little while, said, I've got to get back to my patient.
And see, they had been friends, though, from the time Jack was coordinating commissioner because he arranged for the medical school to have
the same pay from the state with their increase that it cost the state to train a doctor.
And that was part of Jack's coordinating program, so they had known.
And Jaworski was involved in that scene, too.
So these go back to 66, these friendships.
And these were people you could respect.
And so I could see why they liked Jack.
And I think Jack was a respectable person.
Certainly.
And they were too.
And I could see why you would associate yourself with those people.
And they were both leaders in their field.
When did Dr. Williams learn that the board had decided that they were not going to allow him to remain as president of the system and of the university
that they were going to recreate the chancellor job.
The morning that it happened?
The morning of what happened?
We're muting it all the time.
That board meeting where they decided that, was that soon after?
Mr. Wells had asked him to write
about Jarvin.
He said, I've had a lot of letters on him.
And of course, Jack was pushing Calhoun, which I told him it wouldn't work.
But he went to work that morning, and they told him.
And Jack said, first thing he did, he went to the telephone and called me and told me to call the girls.
He did not want them to hear it on the radio or read it in the paper.
He left that group and called me.
Then he went back and asked them, did they have anybody to run the meeting?
And they said no, and he held the meeting for them.
And then at the end of presiding over their meeting, after they'd just fired him when he got to work that day, he went back and got up and said, this is my final meeting.
But he also told them, which Jarvis had to know, that Jarvis was not qualified.
He said, why don't you give him something to do and let him get some experience?
And, of course, Jarvis knew that because...
I'm trying to think of this man that worked for Jack as his assistant, the board secretary.
Oh, oh.
Bob Cherry.
Bob Cherry.
You should be telling these stories.
You know all right his name.
When Jack went to College Station first time, Fort Albright told him to fire Bob Cherry.
And Jack said, I couldn't come out here and start firing people.
And...
He learned and he realized later on that Bob was not loyal.
Dr. Williams told me one day that the biggest mistake he made was not taking that advice when he first received it.
He said he's ingratiating himself to the board now that I can't do it.
Isn't that saying that he had to put up with... See, I think Jack was about the most loyal person to the university that anybody could be.
and to his friends, and he had to tolerate Bob Cherry.
Now, y'all moved over to the board house, the old Board of Regents house just north of Sabeasa, a few weeks?
No, it was later than that.
We stayed in Preston's house for quite a while until Jarvis said he needed to entertain.
He needed it.
And we were glad to...
No, but we also knew now, when we were in the board house, I'm the person that, that was my decision.
I told them get rid of the rats and the bugs, that I couldn't live with rats and bugs, which that was noted for, that I never lived with anything like that.
But since I already knew, Phil Hoffman.
That's the president of the University of Houston that we couldn't remember.
See what I'm saying?
Names come to you when you're not trying to think of their name.
What did you furnish that board house with?
Whose furniture was that?
Mine.
So, some that had, well, you took it out of storage, and some of it had been in storage, and others... Yeah, uh-huh.
And how long were you all there before the house caught fire?
Not very long, but I don't remember the details of it.
Less than a year, I think.
You know, it wasn't because it was...
They had a little trouble in Houston getting rid of the man that they had felt that was not capable of doing what needed to be done, and he was adamant about not leaving.
But they had to do it carefully.
Describe the floor plan of the...
that board house upstairs.
How many bedrooms were there and so forth?
Upstairs?
I don't know.
Oh, no, I'm sorry.
Downstairs.
Downstairs, yeah.
Describe the downstairs area.
What was it?
How many rooms were there?
There was an entrance hall with a, I guess you would say, a living room on one side and a dining area, something on the other side.
I don't remember, and the bedrooms were...
connected.
I had my antique bed in one room and Jack was in the bed in the other room, the one closest to the outside wall.
So were there two bedrooms, three bedrooms?
Two downstairs and a big dining room and two, I guess you'd call it almost a double with the hall splitting the entrance area and two baths on the first floor and the kitchen.
It was okay to live in.
I was very careful about trying to get the blinds to where you couldn't see through them since we were living on the street.
That was my only problem was living on the street, you know, where people could see in.
We talked at lunch about the fire, but to be sure that we get it recorded, describe the night that the building caught fire.
You were saying that... Well, I heard this pounding on the door.
And I got up and went to the door, and one of the security officers from the campus had seen the fire coming out of the roof.
And so he said, I was just ready to kick the door in.
It took me a while to get up and put on a robe and go to the door.
And then Jack got up and said, I'll move the cars.
And he took his, I'm sure he took his medicine, but I know he took his account book out of the fireproof safe.
And he left.
And then I was left with this gentleman.
And he wanted me to show him where to turn off the electricity.
And I dropped my earring.
And until I found my earring, I didn't budge.
And don't you feel that way about something that you have?
But I did pick up my clothes.
And I took them out to the car and dressed in the car.
And we watched the fire people come and go.
And then we went to the motel.
and checked in over there for the night, and a real sweet thing happened.

We had twin beds, and Jack was in bed, and I was in one, and I got up and went around the other side of him, not between the beds, but the other side, got in bed beside me, and I put my arm around him, and he said, my heart didn't stop pounding until you put your arm around me.
That's a special one.
But you never forget that, that my putting my arm around him calmed him down that night because he could have died.
And Jarvis and Bob Cherry were in a car together that night and drove up and saw us sitting in our car.
And I don't remember what was said or if anything was said, but I think Jack just moved our car away from him.
The fire started as far as you know about what time, 2 or 3 o'clock in the morning?
I don't have any idea.
What time did he kick the door in, do you know?
No.
It wouldn't have occurred to me to go see what time it was.
You might go back and find from some record someplace else what time it was, but it wouldn't have occurred to me.
